      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'>Ualdayan</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Since I was around back when they were trying to limit kiting (Pre Kunark) I thought I might be able to find the old patch message easier.  I did a search and on September 13th, 1999 (archive is on eq.castersrealm.com at <a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/archives.asp?Day=13&Month=9&Year=1999&ID=286&Action=View" target="_blank">http://eq.castersrealm.com/archives.asp?Day=13&Month=9&Year=1999&ID=286&Action=View</a>) the following changes were made:</P><P>DoT Changes: <BR>If the monster is in melee with you, there is no change to how a DoT spell works. <BR>If the monster is running away from you (fear, wounded, etc.), there is no change to how a DoT spell works. <BR>If the monster is moving when the damage from the DoT is applied (happens every few seconds), it will take 66% of the damage that it would have taken. <BR>DoT spells have all had their duration slightly increased. If the monster moves for less then 18 seconds during a fight, your DoT will do more damage then it would have done before the patch. If the monster moves more then 18 seconds during the fight, it will take less damage then it would have before the patch. </P><P>OTHER interesting changes in that patch that remind me of the old days and are interesting, but have nothing to do with this are:</P><P>High level pets (44th and 49th lvl spells) do less damage <BR>Dead Man Walking (Necromancer) has been renamed Dead Man Floating <BR>Screaming Terror is now an all or nothing save. This should stop the 'train' problems that it was causing. (this was when Screaming terror was a Fear spell instead of the mez it is now)</P><P><BR>In order to make PVP combat between spellcasters and melee types more viable some changes to PVP spell effects have been made. All damage spells cast in PVP combat will do less damage to the PC than the same spell would do to an NPC. When a PC is under the effect of a root-type spell there is a 20% chance that they will break free when a direct damage spell is cast upon them. </P><P><BR>Ignite Bones (Necromancer) has had the movement component removed. This means that it will no longer break root and snare spells, and that it will now stack with the darkness line.  (GAH, anybody else remember how annoying it was to have to choose between either snare or root since they wouldn't stack with each other)</P><P><BR>Ualdayan Deathwalker, Lvl59 Defiler<BR>Bristlebane</P><P></P><P> </font></td>
